The property of being _normal_ (terrible name, I know)
is similar,
except that instead of _points_ [`x`]($mathtex) and [`y`]($mathtex),
we ask that any pair of _disjoint closed sets_ 
[`A`]($mathtex) and [`B`]($mathtex)
are also contained in disjoint open sets [`U`]($mathtex) and [`V`]($mathtex).

# Urysohn's Lemma

Urysohn's Lemma says that if [`X`]($mathtex) is normal,
then for any pair of disjoint closed sets [`A`]($mathtex) and [`B`]($mathtex),
there is actually a continuous function [`f\colon X \to \mathbb{R}`]($mathtex)
with [`f(a) = 0`]($mathtex) for any point [`a \in A`]($mathtex)
and [`f(b) = 1`]($mathtex) for any point [`b \in B`]($mathtex).

This is kind of amazing to me.
We took a concept based on numbers,
abstracted it so far that spaces like [`\Omega`]($mathtex),
which have nothing to do with numbers,
start to show up,
and then found a definition which gives us back numbers!
How neat is that?

What's more, the proof is really so gorgeous.
Let me give you the first piece of it and then the main idea.
The gorey details will be at the end in case you want to puzzle through them.

## The first step

First, we claim that if [`X`]($mathtex) is normal
and [`A`]($mathtex) is closed, [`U`]($mathtex) is open
and [`A \subset U`]($mathtex),
then there is another open set [`V`]($mathtex), where if we
let [`\overline{V}`]($mathtex) denote its closure,
then we have [`A \subset V \subset \overline{V} \subset U`]($mathtex).

Let's prove that!

So, since [`U`]($mathtex) is open, its complement [`U^c`]($mathtex)
is closed. Since [`A \subset U`]($mathtex),
we have that [`A`]($mathtex) and [`U^c`]($mathtex) are disjoint.
Since [`X`]($mathtex) is normal,
there are disjoint open sets [`A \subset V`]($mathtex)
and [`U^c \subset W`]($mathtex).
The fact that [`V`]($mathtex) and [`W`]($mathtex) are disjoint
actually implies (though not immediately from anything I've written on this page)
that [`\overline{V}`]($mathtex) is disjoint from [`U^c`]($mathtex),
which shows that we have
[`A \subset V \subset \overline{V} \subset U`]($mathtex) as required. [`\blacksquare`]($mathtex)

## The idea

The idea of the proof is to repeatedly use the first step,
filling in open sets in between open sets repeatedly.
As we do so, the contours of the open sets trace out
almost a _topographical map_ of the desired function [`f`]($mathtex)!

## The details

Actually, we can by systematic in numbering these sets
with _dyadic rational numbers_ between 0 and 1—that is,
finite binary decimals.

Here's how: let's call [`A = C_0`]($mathtex) and [`B^c = U_1`]($mathtex).
Using the first step, we construct [`U_{\frac{1}{2}}`]($mathtex)
and [`C_{\frac{1}{2}} = \overline{U_{\frac{1}{2}}}`]($mathtex)
such that [`C_0 \subset U_{\frac{1}{2}} \subset C_{\frac{1}{2}} \subset U_1`]($mathtex).
Repeating the first step, we can fit in

```=mathtex
C_0 \subset U_{\frac{1}{4}} \subset C_{\frac{1}{4}} \subset U_{\frac{1}{2}} \subset
C_{\frac{1}{2}} \subset U_{\frac{3}{4}} \subset C_{\frac{3}{4}} \subset U_1.
```

Clearly we can keep doing this for any finite binary decimal number between 0 and 1.
The beautiful thing about this is that we can use one of the defining properties
of real numbers, the "greatest lower bound" property, to construct the function [`f`]($mathtex).
Namely, define

```=mathtex
f(x) = \inf \left\{ \frac{p}{2^n} \in \mathbb{Q} : x \in U_{\frac{p}{2^n}} \right\}.
```
